  "narrative_summary": "=================================================================\nEQUITY & DATA JUSTICE ANALYSIS \u2014 NARRATIVE SUMMARY\n=================================================================\n\nAnalysis covered 20 EU countries with both metadata\nsufficiency scores and Eurostat socioeconomic indicators.\n\nSIGNIFICANT CORRELATIONS (p < 0.05):\n\n  \u2022 composite score \u2194 E-Government Usage (%): \u03c1=-0.446, p=0.049 (negative)\n  \u2022 composite score \u2194 Data Infrastructure Score: \u03c1=-0.454, p=0.044 (negative)\n\nMARGINAL CORRELATIONS (0.05 \u2264 p < 0.10):\n\n  \u2022 compliance reporting score \u2194 E-Government Usage (%): \u03c1=-0.393, p=0.087 (marginal, negative)\n  \u2022 compliance reporting score \u2194 Data Infrastructure Score: \u03c1=-0.439, p=0.053 (marginal, negative)\n  \u2022 cross border score \u2194 E-Government Usage (%): \u03c1=-0.443, p=0.050 (marginal, negative)\n\nDIRECTION OF EFFECT SUMMARY (Spearman \u03c1):\n  Score                                    GDP     DESI      WEI      ODM\n  -----------------------------------   ------   ------   ------   ------\n  early warning score                  -0.072   -0.043   -0.101   -0.349 \n  compliance reporting score           -0.295   -0.249   +0.133   -0.370 \n  cross border score                   -0.188   -0.156   +0.075   -0.057 \n  composite score                      -0.333   -0.273   +0.064   -0.310 \n\n  * p<0.05,  \u00b7 p<0.10\n\nOVERALL DATA QUALITY LEVEL:\n  Mean sufficiency score across all countries: 0.232 / 1.0\n  This corresponds to Partial / Insufficient quality overall.\n  The limiting factors are predominantly:\n    - Missing machine-readable formats (zero or minimal coverage)\n    - No open licenses declared\n    - Poor temporal coverage and update-frequency metadata\n    - Low description quality (short or absent abstracts)\n\nDATA JUSTICE CONCLUSION:\n\n  The analysis does NOT find strong evidence that poorer or less\n  digitally developed EU countries produce systematically lower-quality\n  water metadata. Instead, quality gaps are pervasive across all wealth\n  levels, suggesting that the primary bottleneck is sector-level practice\n  (water administration) rather than national digital capacity.\n\n  However, the available country-level sample (n \u2264 27) is small.\n  A sub-national analysis or targeted survey would better reveal\n  whether resource constraints amplify local data quality disparities."
